Description: CVE-2026-34588: prevent signed int overflow in PIZ decompression
 An attacker-controlled EXR file can specify channel dimensions whose
 products (nx*size, nx*ny*size) overflow signed 32-bit int, advancing
 the wavelet working pointer by a wrapped value. This causes
 out-of-bounds reads and writes in wav2Decode (called from
 PizCompressor::uncompress) and wav2Encode (called from
 PizCompressor::compress).
 .
 Add an early validation of channel dimensions at the start of the
 wavelet codec path so that overflow-inducing inputs are rejected with
 InputExc before any wavelet/pointer arithmetic occurs. As a
 belt-and-suspenders measure, also widen the cumulative
 tmpBufferEnd advance to size_t so the per-channel layout offset
 cannot wrap a 32-bit signed int.
 .
 The guard is placed once per function (compress and uncompress) right
 before the wav2Encode/wav2Decode loops, after the channel-data
 population loop has filled cd.nx, cd.ny, cd.size. Because wav2Decode
 and wav2Encode are only called from PizCompressor, this single guard
 is sufficient to cover all three vulnerable sites identified upstream
 (the call-site oy = nx*size, the inner-loop oy*p / oy*p2 / oy*(ny-p2)
 products, and the per-channel buffer advance nx*ny*size).
 .
 This mirrors the upstream OpenEXR 3.x fix
 (commit ca0139287918775e1fddc0ed0033d694bec033ff in
 src/lib/OpenEXRCore/internal_piz.c) adapted for the C++
 implementation in OpenEXR 2.5.4 (OpenEXR/IlmImf/ImfPizCompressor.cpp).
