Description: Fix CVE-2026-34589 signed integer overflow in LossyDctDecoder
 numBlocksX and numBlocksY are declared as int. Two pointer-offset
 expressions in DwaCompressor::LossyDctDecoderBase::execute() multiplied
 them as signed 32-bit integers before using the result as a pointer
 offset:
 .
     rowBlock[comp]   = rowBlock[comp - 1]   + numBlocksX * 64;
     currDcComp[comp] = currDcComp[comp - 1] + numBlocksX * numBlocksY;
 .
 dataWindow.max.x is a signed 32-bit value in the EXR file format, so
 numBlocksX can reach (INT32_MAX + 7) / 8 = 268,435,456. At that point
 numBlocksX * 64 overflows int32, and numBlocksX * numBlocksY overflows
 even sooner. The wraparound produces a small or negative pointer offset,
 causing rowBlock[comp] and currDcComp[comp] to point into already-used
 or pre-buffer memory rather than the intended component stride, leading
 to a heap out-of-bounds write (CWE-787) when a crafted scanline DWAA EXR
 file is decoded.
 .
 Fix: cast numBlocksX to size_t before multiplying so the arithmetic is
 performed in pointer-sized unsigned arithmetic.
 .
 Backported from the OpenEXR 3.x C-API
 (src/lib/OpenEXRCore/internal_dwa_decoder.h, LossyDctDecoder_execute)
 to the legacy IlmImf C++ library (OpenEXR/IlmImf/ImfDwaCompressor.cpp,
 DwaCompressor::LossyDctDecoderBase::execute) shipped in 2.5.4.
Origin: upstream, https://github.com/AcademySoftwareFoundation/openexr/commit/9ad6c97548a54fea8d2fdc1a06883bbba7c5c9c3
