--- /dev/null
+++ b/ROOT-SECURITY-RELEASE-CVE-2026-34543.md
@@ -0,0 +1,163 @@
+# CVE-2026-34543 — Not Affected Analysis for OpenEXR 2.5.4 (Debian Bullseye)
+
+## Summary
+
+CVE-2026-34543 does **not** affect OpenEXR 2.5.4. Any scanner flagging this version is
+producing a false positive based on package-name matching alone. The vulnerable code
+path lives in the OpenEXRCore C library (3.4.x regression) and does not exist in the
+2.x series shipped by Debian Bullseye.
+
+---
+
+## CVE Description
+
+> OpenEXR provides the specification and reference implementation of the EXR file format,
+> an image storage format for the motion picture industry. From version **3.4.0** to before
+> version **3.4.8**, sensitive information from heap memory may be leaked through the decoded
+> pixel data (information disclosure). This occurs under default settings; simply reading a
+> malicious EXR file is sufficient to trigger the issue, without any user interaction.
+> This issue has been patched in version 3.4.8.
+
+**Affected range:** 3.4.0 ≤ version < 3.4.8
+**Fixed in:** 3.4.8
+**Debian Bullseye ships:** OpenEXR **2.5.4** (package `openexr` version `2.5.4-2+deb11u1`)
+
+2.5.4 is below the affected lower bound of 3.4.0 by an entire major branch.
+
+---
+
+## Root Cause of the Vulnerability (in 3.4.0–3.4.7)
+
+PXR24 compression stores zlib-compressed **packed** channel data (3 bytes/sample for
+FLOAT, 2 bytes/sample for HALF, 4 bytes/sample for UINT), while the chunk's
+`unpacked_size` field uses the native in-memory layout (4 bytes/sample for FLOAT/UINT).
+
+In versions 3.4.0–3.4.7, after calling the decompression function the decoder validated
+consumed bytes against `uncompressed_size` (the native layout size) rather than against
+the **actual number of bytes produced by zlib** (`outSize` / `actual_out`). A
+truncated-but-valid zlib stream could therefore decompress to fewer bytes than expected
+while returning success; the decoder would then advance read pointers through the scratch
+buffer as if the full packed block were present, reading uninitialized heap bytes into
+decoded pixel output — an information disclosure.
+
+The fix (commit `5f6d0aaa9e43802917af7db90f181e88e083d3b8`, released in 3.4.8) changed
+those comparisons to use the actual decompressed byte count instead of `uncompressed_size`.
+
+---
+
+## Why 2.5.4 Is Not Affected
+
+### 1. The vulnerable files do not exist in 2.5.4
+
+The upstream fix touches two files, both belonging to the **OpenEXRCore** C library that
+was introduced as part of the OpenEXR 3.x reorganization:
+
+| Upstream fix file | Present in 2.5.4? |
+|-------------------|-------------------|
+| `src/lib/OpenEXRCore/internal_pxr24.c` | **No** |
+| `src/lib/OpenEXRCore/compression.c`    | **No** |
+
+OpenEXR 2.5.4 has no `src/lib/OpenEXRCore/` directory at all — in fact, it has no
+top-level `src/` directory. The 2.x layout is:
+
+```
+OpenEXR/IlmImf/        <- legacy C++ IlmImf library (the only EXR codec in 2.x)
+IlmBase/               <- math + half + thread support libraries
+PyIlmBase/             <- Python bindings
+OpenEXR_Viewers/       <- sample viewers
+```
+
+Since the regression that introduced the bug was made directly inside
+`internal_pxr24.c` and `compression.c`, neither of which exists in 2.5.4, the
+vulnerable code path is structurally absent.
+
+### 2. The legacy C++ PXR24 decoder uses the protective `tmpSize` pattern
+
+In 2.5.4, PXR24 decompression is handled by `OpenEXR/IlmImf/ImfPxr24Compressor.cpp`
+inside `Pxr24Compressor::uncompress`. It calls zlib's `::uncompress()` directly and
+captures the **actual** number of bytes written via `tmpSize`:
+
+```cpp
+// tmpSize starts as the expected size and is updated by zlib to the actual
+// number of bytes written on return.
+uLongf tmpSize = _maxScanLineSize * _numScanLines;
+
+if (Z_OK != ::uncompress ((Bytef *)_tmpBuffer,
+                          &tmpSize,
+                          (const Bytef *) inPtr,
+                          inSize))
+{
+    throw IEX_NAMESPACE::InputExc ("Data decompression (zlib) failed.");
+}
+```
+
+Each per-channel decode loop then bounds-checks against `tmpSize` (the actual
+zlib output length), not against the requested expected size:
+
+```cpp
+if ((uLongf)(tmpBufferEnd - _tmpBuffer) > tmpSize)
+    notEnoughData();   // throws InputExc, aborts decoding
+```
+
+This guard is repeated for every pixel-type branch (UINT, HALF, FLOAT) and there is
+a final post-loop check `(uLongf)(tmpBufferEnd - _tmpBuffer) < tmpSize` which catches
+any "too much data" case as well. This is exactly the same protective pattern that
+the 3.4.8 fix restores in the OpenEXRCore C rewrite. It was never broken in the 2.x
+C++ implementation.
+
+### 3. No `exr_uncompress_buffer()` wrapper exists in 2.5.4
+
+The second part of the upstream fix updates a comment in `compression.c` regarding
+libdeflate's `LIBDEFLATE_SHORT_OUTPUT` return code. There is no `exr_uncompress_buffer`
+helper in 2.5.4 — zlib is the only decompressor and is invoked directly inside the
+C++ compressor classes. This portion of the fix is entirely not applicable.
+
+---
+
+## Timeline
+
+| Date | Event |
+|------|-------|
+| Apr 2021 | OpenEXR 2.5.4 released — legacy C++ IlmImf only, `tmpSize`-based guards |
+| 2022 | OpenEXR 3.x introduces new C `OpenEXRCore` library (`src/lib/OpenEXRCore/`) |
+| 2023–2024 | Regression introduced in 3.4.0 branch: guards changed to `uncompressed_size` |
+| 2026-03-22 | CVE-2026-34543 fixed in commit `5f6d0aaa` (3.4.8) |
+| 2026-04-10 | CVE published, affected range declared as 3.4.0 – 3.4.7 |
+
+---
+
+## Scanner False Positive Explanation
+
+Automated vulnerability scanners (Trivy, Grype, Snyk, Dependabot, etc.) typically match
+CVEs against a package name and version range sourced from the NVD CPE data. Because the
+NVD entry states the vulnerable component is `openexr`, some scanners flag **any** version
+of the `openexr` / `libopenexr*` packages without checking whether the installed version
+is within the stated 3.4.0–3.4.7 range. This is a known limitation of range-based CPE
+matching when a CVE's lower bound is not `0` or `*`.
+
+**Debian Bullseye ships 2.5.4, which is below the lower bound of 3.4.0 by an entire
+major branch. The package is not vulnerable.**
+
+---
+
+## Recommended Disposition
+
+| Field | Value |
